unique(ufc_men$RedStance)
## [1] "Orthodox"    "Southpaw"    "Switch"      "Open Stance"
unique(ufc_men$BetterRank)
## [1] "Red"     "neither" "Blue"
unique(ufc_men$Finish)
## [1] "SUB"        "U-DEC"      "S-DEC"      "KO/TKO"     "M-DEC"     
## [6] "DQ"         NA           "Overturned"
## fix NA values in Finish
sum(is.na(ufc_men$Finish))
## [1] 196
ufc_men$Finish[is.na(ufc_men$Finish)] <- "Unknown"
  • there were 196 NA finishes, I replaced them with unknown
## remove overturned results 
ufc_men <- ufc_men[ufc_men$Finish != "Overturned", ]
  • there were 8 overturned results, I removed them
## convert to factors
ufc_men$Winner <- as.factor(ufc_men$Winner)
ufc_men$WeightClass <- factor(ufc_men$WeightClass, levels = c("Flyweight", "Bantamweight", "Featherweight",
                                                               "Lightweight", "Welterweight", "Middleweight",
                                                               "Light Heavyweight", "Heavyweight", "Catch Weight"))

ufc_men$BlueStance <- as.factor(trimws(ufc_men$BlueStance)) 
ufc_men$BetterRank <- as.factor(ufc_men$BetterRank)
ufc_men$Finish <- as.factor(trimws(ufc_men$Finish))

Wins by Weight Class

ggplot(ufc_men, aes(x = WeightClass, fill = Winner)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Red" = "red", "Blue" = "blue")) +  # Ensure correct colors
  labs(title = "Win Rate by Weight Class", y = "Proportion", x = "Weight Class", fill = "Winner") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

- Win rate by weight class is pretty evenly distributed among the weight classes, red fighters seem to win more often across all weight classes.

Win rate by odds and expected value

# Red Fighter Odds Plot
p1 <- ggplot(ufc_men, aes(x = RedOdds, fill = Winner)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 50, position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Red" = "red", "Blue" = "blue")) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(-2000, 1000, 500), labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Win Rate by Red Fighter Odds",

Odds Ratios

# Compute Ratios
ufc_men$OddsRatio <- abs(ufc_men$RedOdds / ufc_men$BlueOdds)
ufc_men$EVRatio <- abs(ufc_men$RedExpectedValue / ufc_men$BlueExpectedValue)

# Log Transform (optional, prevents extreme values from dominating)
ufc_men$LogOddsRatio <- log(ufc_men$OddsRatio)
ufc_men$LogEVRatio <- log(ufc_men$EVRatio)
ggplot(ufc_men, aes(x = OddsRatio, fill = Winner)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1, position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Red" = "red", "Blue" = "blue")) +
  labs(title = "Win Rate by Odds Ratio",
       x = "Odds Ratio (Red/Blue)",
       y = "Proportion of Wins",
       fill = "Winner") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).
## Warning: Removed 38 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range

- If Odds Ratio > 1, Red was the underdog. - If Odds Ratio < 1, Blue was the underdog. - Odds ratio is a strong predictor given it is outside bounds of 1.2 and 1.5

Significant Strikes

ggplot(ufc_men, aes(x = SigStrDif, fill = Winner)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "fill") +
  facet_wrap(~WeightClass, scales = "free_y") +  # Separate by weight class
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Red" = "red", "Blue" = "blue")) +
  labs(title = "Win Rate by Significant Strike Difference Across Weight Classes",
       x = "Significant Strike Difference",
       y = "Proportion of Wins",
       fill = "Winner") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 388 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_bar()`).

-lighter Weight Classes (Bantamweight, Flyweight, Featherweight, Lightweight): More striking volume overall. Fighters with higher SigStrDif tend to win more. Striking differential seems to have a stronger impact on winning.

-Heavier Weight Classes (Middleweight, Light Heavyweight, Heavyweight): Striking differential appears less critical. More fights are won with low or even negative SigStrDif. This suggests more KO power, grappling, or lower volume exchanges are bigger factors.

-Catch Weight & Welterweight: More scattered results. Possible smaller sample size for Catch Weight makes trends less obvious. This is a common occurrence for these weight classes.

Take Downs

  facet_wrap(~WeightClass, scales = "free_y") +

       x = "Takedown Difference",
       y = "Proportion of Wins",
       fill = "Winner") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 132 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_bar()`).

-Takedown Difference Matters More in Heavier Divisions (Middleweight, Light Heavyweight, Heavyweight)

As AvgTDDif increases, win probability also increases. Fighters with more takedowns generally win in heavier classes. This uggests that grappling and control time are more important at higher weights.

  • Lighter Weight Classes (Bantamweight, Flyweight, Featherweight, Lightweight) Less reliance on take downs suggesting striking may play a bigger role. Common for fighters to still win despite a take down disadvantage. Flyweight and Featherweight show a mixed pattern, meaning ground game isnt always the deciding factor.

-Catch Weight & Welterweight Again, scattered results, possibly due to a smaller sample size. Welterweight follows a similar trend as middleweight but with more variability.

  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, position = "fill") +
  facet_wrap(~WeightClass, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Red" = "red", "Blue" = "blue")) +
  labs(title = "Win Rate by KO/TKO Difference Across Weight Classes",
       x = "KO/TKO Difference",
       y = "Proportion of Wins",
       fill = "Winner") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 324 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_bar()`).

  • KO/TKO Difference is More Predictive in Heavier Weight Classes (Middleweight, Light Heavyweight, Heavyweight)

As KODif increases (fighter has more career KOs), their win probability increases. This suggests that KO power is a strong predictor of success in heavier divisions. Heavyweight, Light Heavyweight, and Middleweight divisions show clear trends where fighters with a KO advantage tend to win more often.

-KO/TKO Difference is Less Predictive in Lighter Weight Classes (Bantamweight, Flyweight, Featherweight, Lightweight)

KO power seems to matter less in lower weight classes, which aligns with expectations since these fighters rely more on speed, volume striking, and decisions. There are more mixed results, meaning that fighters can still win despite having fewer career KOs.

Featherweight and Flyweight show relatively balanced win rates, meaning knockout experience isnt a dominant factor in these divisions.

-Catch Weight & Welterweight

Catch Weight lacks clear trends, possibly due to a small sample size.

Additional Betting Odds

These are Set by Sportsbooks and Reflect Market Expectations

# Select only betting odds columns
betting_odds <- ufc_men[, c("RedDecOdds", "BlueDecOdds", "RSubOdds", "BSubOdds", "RKOOdds", "BKOOdds")]

# Convert to long format for easier plotting
betting_odds_long <- melt(betting_odds)
## No id variables; using all as measure variables
# Plot distribution
ggplot(betting_odds_long, aes(x = value, fill = variable)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 50, alpha = 0.7, position = "identity") +
  facet_wrap(~variable, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Betting Odds", x = "Odds", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 6992 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).

- Decision Odds (RedDecOdds, BlueDecOdds) These are mostly negative to low positive values. Strongly skewed toward low odds (favored outcomes). Suggests that decision wins are the most common or at least expected frequently.

  • Submission Odds (RSubOdds, BSubOdds) Much wider range, with many values above +1000. This suggests submissions are often viewed as underdog outcomes. Higher variance means sports books rarely predict subs as likely.

  • KO/TKO Odds (RKOOdds, BKOOdds) More normally distributed than submissions. KO wins are expected more often than subs but less than decisions. Few extreme values compared to submission odds.

Odds Correlation with Outcome

# Compute correlation matrix
cor(ufc_men[, c("RedDecOdds", "BlueDecOdds", "RSubOdds", "BSubOdds", "RKOOdds", "BKOOdds")], 
    as.numeric(ufc_men$Winner == "Red"), use = "complete.obs")
##                   [,1]
## RedDecOdds  -0.1745153
## BlueDecOdds  0.2283873
## RSubOdds    -0.1507795
## BSubOdds     0.1751522
## RKOOdds     -0.1963483
## BKOOdds      0.2164072

Red Decision: -0.17, Lower decision odds or red result in a higher probability red fighter will win, Market odds are a strong predictor of the winner.

Blue Decision: .23, Higher decision odds or blue result in a higher probability red fighters will win, not common for underdogs to win by decision.

Red Submission: -0.15, Market odds are a strong predictor of the winner of red fighters via submission.

Blue Submission: 0.18, if odds predict blue to loos by submission books are generally correct.

Red KO/TKO: -0.20, Low odds for red fighters to win by KO/TKO are a strong predictor

Blue KO/TKO: 0.22, if odds are low for blue fighters to win by KO/TKO it is generally uncommon.

KO/TKO odds are the most predictive of the outcome, followed by decision odds, and then submission odds.
